# Yulin Zhang, 2026.2.24

This folder contains scripts used to run TRACE on SINGER outputs and annotate TRACE outputs. 

The final result tables from these analysis could be downloaded from Zenodo:
**************

We would use the example below to show how to use the scripts and workflow.

## Step 1: run TRACE

Here we would show how to run TRACE on SINGER outputs `yri_chr1_{250..299}.tsz` (example outputs from the workflows in folder `../singer/`). We would assume the tree sequences are built on 100 diploid YRI individuals (200 haplotypes).

To extract input data for TRACE from these tree files:

```
# $i is from {250..299}; strictmask_chr1.bed is the 1000 Genomes strict accessibility mask
indivs=$(printf "%d," {0..49} | sed 's/,$//')
trace-extract --tree-file yri_chr1_${i}.tsz --t-archaic 15000 --individuals ${indivs} --include-regions strictmask_chr1.bed --chrom chr1 --window-size 1000 -o singer_chr1_t15000_strictmask_${i}_ind0_49
```

Here we show example for extracting data for 50 haplotypes at once (so one needs to run 4 times for 200 haplotypes). We run this step in this way to save memory usage and speed up downstream I/O. This step needs to cover all haplotypes and all posterior tree sequences.

To run TRACE on each haplotype (0-199, showing 0 as example below):

```
# create input data files for TRACE per chromosome
for c in {1..22}
do
    for i in {250..299}
    do
        cat singer_chr${c}_t15000_strictmask_${i}_ind0_49.npz >> singer_data_chr${c}.txt
    done
done

datafile_string=$(printf "singer_data_chr%d.txt," {1..22} | sed 's/,$//')
chrom_string=$(printf "chr%d," {1..22} | sed 's/,$//')
gmap_string=$(printf "genetic_map_hg38_chr%d.txt," {1..22} | sed 's/,$//')

# This would produce 22 output files, one file per chromosome: trace_t15000_strictmask_ind0_chr{1..22}.xss.npz
> trace-infer -i 0 --data-files $datafile_string --chroms $chrom_string --genetic-maps $gmap_string -o trace_t15000_strictmask_ind0
```

We run `trace-infer` combining 22 chromosomes together for each individual. This step needs to cover all haplotypes (0-199).

To get final outputs from TRACE:

```
# This would produce trace_t15000_strictmask_ind0.chr1.summary.txt
trace-summarize -f trace_t15000_strictmask_ind0.chr1.xss.npz -c chr1 -o trace_t15000_strictmask_ind0_chr1
```

We run `trace-summarize` with default settings separately for each individual haplotype each chromosome.

## Step 2: record SNP information

In the `snpinfo` directory, we provide the snakemake workflow to annotate each SNP. To run the workflow, one needs to edit the `config.yaml` file to change the paths. If all paths are correctly specified, one could turn enable to True and run
```
snakemake --dry-run
```
and see no error message produced. The output files from this workflow are named as `1000g_biall_snpinfo.human_ancestor.archaic.afr.outgroup.strictmask.mutage.chr{chrom}.txt`

Note the snpinfo files need to be generated independantly for different populations if they are not included in the same SINGER ARGs -- the mutation age estimations would differ in this case.

## Step 3: annotate TRACE outputs

After getting TRACE summary files from Step 1 and SNP info files from Step 2, one could use `annotate_trace_realdata.py` to annotate the TRACE detected archaic segments.

```
> python annotate_trace_realdata.py -h
usage: annotate_trace_realdata.py [-h] --ind IND --inpref INPREF --chrom CHROM --sample-info SAMPLE_INFO --xss-pref XSS_PREF [--hmmix-path HMMIX_PATH] --ibdmix-path IBDMIX_PATH --snpinfo-pref SNPINFO_PREF
                                  --bcf-pref BCF_PREF [--classify-group {1,2}] --outpref OUTPREF

Generate sbatch job files for singer submission. Please modify exclude regions in the code.

options:
  -h, --help            show this help message and exit
  --ind IND             individual ID
  --inpref INPREF       input summary file prefix (parts before .summary.txt)
  --chrom CHROM         chromosome, must match the chromosome field in input summary file
  --sample-info SAMPLE_INFO
                        sample information file
  --xss-pref XSS_PREF   prefix for xss files (parts before .[chrom].xss.npz)
  --hmmix-path HMMIX_PATH
                        path to hmmix decoded outputs, assume file names are [samplename].hap[1/2].txt;if not provided, will skip appending hmmix info and only use ibdmix for annotation
  --ibdmix-path IBDMIX_PATH
                        path to ibdmix outputs, assume file names are [chrom].txt
  --snpinfo-pref SNPINFO_PREF
                        prefix to snpinfo file with mutation age info appended (parts before .[chrom].txt)
  --bcf-pref BCF_PREF   prefix to bcf files for extracting allele frequency info, assume file names are [prefix][chrom].bcf
  --classify-group {1,2}
                        classification rule group for final annotation, 1 for more stringent classification and 2 for more relaxed classification
  --outpref OUTPREF     output prefix for the final annotated tables, file names will be [outpref].count_merge.txt
```

One example run using the outputs from above could be

```
python annotate_trace_realdata.py --ind 0 --inpref trace_t15000_strictmask_ind0_chr1 --chrom chr1 --sample-info treeID.txt --xss-pref trace_t15000_strictmask_ind0 --hmmix-path hmmix/02decode/ --ibdmix-path ibdmix/EUR/ --snpinfo-pref 1000g_biall_snpinfo.human_ancestor.archaic.afr.outgroup.strictmask.mutage --bcf-pref bcf_files/1000g_hg38_ --outpref test
```

The `treeID.txt` file could be found in Table_S3.xslx in supplementary data from the manuscript for different populations. An example of the file structure is

```
> head -n 5 treeID.txt
ID      Name    SampleID        Population      SuperGroup
0       HG00096.hap1    HG00096 GBR     EUR
1       HG00096.hap2    HG00096 GBR     EUR
2       HG00097.hap1    HG00097 GBR     EUR
3       HG00097.hap2    HG00097 GBR     EUR
```

